com.apriori.collections

Interface ConcurrentList<E>

  • Type Parameters:
    E - the type of element in the list
    All Superinterfaces:
    Collection<E>, Iterable<E>, List<E>
    All Known Implementing Classes:
    PersistentListBackedConcurrentList

    public interface ConcurrentList<E>
extends List<E>
    A list that is thread-safe and supports concurrent mutations. In addition to standard list operations, several atomic operations are provided to enable concurrent updates.

    Iterators returned by this interface will not throw ConcurrentModificationExceptions during traversal. However, this exception can still be thrown from modification operations made through the iterator: (Iterator.remove(), ListIterator.add(Object), and ListIterator.set(Object)). Whether or not such exceptions are thrown depends on a given implementation of this interface. But the only operations guaranteed to not throw are traversal/query operations.

    This interface does not specify whether Iterators are weakly consistent or are strongly consistent snaphots. That detail, as well as the conditions which are considered "conflicting concurrent modifications", should be documented by concrete sub-classes.

      • addAfter

        boolean addAfter(int index,
                 E expectedPriorValue,
                 E addition)
        Adds the given value at the given index, after the given value. This atomically adds the value at the given index but only if its predecessor would match the given value.

        The given index will be the index of the newly added item. Any items at that index or after will be shifted by one. The expected prior value is compared against the item at index - 1 and the operation is aborted if the actual value doesn't match.

        Parameters:
        index - the index of the newly added item
        expectedPriorValue - the expected value of the new element's predecessor
        addition - the value to add at the given index
        Returns:
        true if the value was added or false if the element's predecessor differed from the expected value

      • addBefore

        boolean addBefore(int index,
                  E expectedNextValue,
                  E addition)
        Adds the given value at the given index, before the given value. This atomically adds the value at the given index but only if its successor would match the given value.

        The given index will be the index of the newly added item. Any items at that index or after will be shifted by one. The expected next value is compared against the item already at the given index (which will be shifted to index + 1 after the operation completes). The operation is aborted if the actual value doesn't match.

        Parameters:
        index - the index of the newly added item
        expectedNextValue - the expected value of the new element's successor
        addition - the value to add at the given index
        Returns:
        true if the value was added or false if the element's succcessor differed from the expected value

      • addFirst

        default void addFirst(E newValue)
        Adds an element to the beginning of the list. The indices for all other elements in the list, if any, are shifted by one. This method is named for readability and can be used in place of addAfter(int, Object, Object) when there is no predecessor.

        The default implementation is simply the following:
        add(0, newValue).

        Parameters:
        newValue - the value to add to the front of the list

        Parameters:

        Returns:

      • subList

        ConcurrentList<E> subList(int fromIndex,
                          int toIndex)
        Returns a view of the portion of this list between the specified indices. Changes to this list are visible through the returned view, and vice versa.

        The returned list is also a concurrent list. Structural changes made to the underlying list can impact the returned list. For example, if an element is added in the given index range in the underlying list, it will effectively displace the last element of the sub-list (since that last item has now been pushed beyond the end of the index range). Similarly, removing an element in the given index range from the underlying list will cause the sub-list to get a new last element (the item that was after the given range that has now been pulled into the range due to an element removal).

        The returned sub-list should never throw ConcurrentModificationException from any of its operations (although its iterators may throw this exception if concurrent modifications conflict with attempts to modify the list via the iterator).

        Unlike the standard List interface, implementations may choose to return an unmodifiable view. In that case, changes made to the underlying list are visible via the sub-list view. But the sub-list view itself may throw UnsupportedOperationException for structural modifications, like adding and removing elements.

        Specified by:
        subList in interface List<E>
        See Also:
        List.subList(int, int)

      • tailList

        ConcurrentList<E> tailList(int fromIndex)
        Returns a view of the tail of this list. Changes to this list are visible through the returned view, and vice versa.

        This is similar to using subList(fromIndex, size()) except that the returned list can grow as the underlying list grows. If an element is added after the given index, it will not displace the last element of the sub-list but instead extend it.

        Like subList(int, int), implementations may choose to return an unmodifiable view, in which case the returned view can throw UnsupportedOperationException when structural modifications are attempted.

        Parameters:
        fromIndex - low endpoint (inclusive) of the tail list
        Returns:
        a view of the specified range within this list
